The ratio test involves finding the limit (\(L\)) as \(n\) approaches infinity of the absolute value of the ratio between the "\(n\)th plus one" term of a sequence and the \(n\)th term. What can be concluded from this test?
Option 1: If \(L<0\), the series converges; if \(L=0\), the series converges conditionally; if \(L>0\), the series diverges
Option 2: If \(L<1\), the series converges; if \(L=1\), the series converges conditionally; if \(L>1\), the series diverges
Option 3: If \(L=0\), the series converges; if \(L=\infty\) or \(L=- \infty\), the series diverges; otherwise, the test is inconclusive
Option 4: If \(L=0\), the series diverges; if \(L=\infty\) or \(L=- \infty\), the series converges; otherwise, the test is inconclusive
Option 5: If \(L<1\), the series converges; if \(L>1\), the series diverges; if \(L=1\), the test is inconclusive
